It

the
Dog

A
FEW
years
ago,
a
couple
of
Dutchmen
upon
the

high

of
Limestone,
though
very
friendly,
had

a
dreadful
falling
out
about
one
killing
the
other's
dog,

for
which
he
sued
for
damages.
They
were
called
into

court,
and
the
defendant
in
the
case
was
asked
by
the

judge,
if
he
killed
the
dog?
"Pe
sure
I
kilt
him,"
said

the
Dutchman,
"but
let
him
proof
it."
This
being
quite

satisfactory,
the
plaintiff
in
the
case
was
called
on
to
an

swer
a
few
questions;
he
was
asked
by
the
judge,
to
what

amount
he
estimated
his
damages?
He
did
not
under

stand
this
question
so
well,
so
to
be
a
little
plainer,
the

judge
asked
him
what
he
thought
the
dog
to
be
worth?

"Pe
sure,"
said
he,"the
dog
was
wot
noting;
but
since
he

was
so
mean
as
to
kill
him,
he
shall
pay
de
full
walue
of
him."

Watering
Milk

A
Dutchman
in
Albany
some
time
back,
went
out
to

his
milkman
in
the
street
with
a
dish
in
each
hand,

instead
of
one
as
usual.
The
dispenser
of
attenuated
milk

asked
if
he
wished
him
to
fill
both
vessels?
The
Dutch

man
replied,
suiting
the
action
to
the
word,
"Dis
is
for

de
milluk,
and
dis
for
de
waiter —and
I
will
mix
dem
so

as
to
shute
mineself."
